</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B998C0A7152B005FF7850F4FC8F11B9" blockId="3.[136,1452,158,580]" box="[189,862,194,220]" pageId="3" pageNumber="109">
<emphasis id="B95250187152B005FF7850F4FE8E11B9" bold="true" box="[189,351,194,220]" pageId="3" pageNumber="109">Phenology:—</emphasis>
Flowers collected in the last week of January.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B998C0A7152B005FF7850D3FE7A10BD" blockId="3.[136,1452,158,580]" pageId="3" pageNumber="109">
<emphasis id="B95250187152B005FF7850D3FDCC1065" bold="true" box="[189,541,229,256]" pageId="3" pageNumber="109">IUCN-conservation status:—</emphasis>
A first assessment results in “Data Deficient”, since the extent of occurrence cannot be calculated with only two data points. However, in the last decades many collections have been made in 
<collectingCountry id="F331CC9A7152B005FF4D5118FF04102D" box="[136,213,302,328]" name="Gabon" pageId="3" pageNumber="109">Gabon</collectingCountry>
, and for the revision we have seen almost all collections of 
<taxonomicName id="4C26F7897152B005FCA25118FBDE102D" authorityName="Baillon" authorityYear="1890" box="[871,1039,302,328]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Monanthotaxis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="3" pageNumber="109" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95250187152B005FCA25118FBDE102D" box="[871,1039,302,328]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="109">Monanthotaxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry id="F331CC9A7152B005FBF45118FBAD102D" box="[1073,1148,302,328]" name="Gabon" pageId="3" pageNumber="109">Gabon</collectingCountry>
and surrounding countries. No other material has thus far been found. Therefore, the species seems to be genuinely rare (see also the discussion). Furthermore, both collections have been made in unprotected areas, one of which is in danger because of the expanding city of Libreville. The other collection has been made in a logging area, and therefore we suggest the status endangered: B2 ab(iii) for this species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B998C0A7152B005FF7851D4FC7F1321" blockId="3.[136,1452,158,580]" pageId="3" pageNumber="109">
<emphasis id="B95250187152B005FF7851D4FEF71099" bold="true" box="[189,294,482,508]" pageId="3" pageNumber="109">Notes:—</emphasis>
A black swollen leaf margin at the base of the leaf is a common feature in many species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C26F7897152B005FB3951D4FA751099" authorityName="Baillon" authorityYear="1890" box="[1276,1444,482,508]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Monanthotaxis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="3" pageNumber="109" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95250187152B005FB3951D4FA751099" box="[1276,1444,482,508]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="109">Monanthotaxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In most literature, it is referred to as glands (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB7F1FB7152B005FD6F5230FCBB1345" author="Le Thomas, A." box="[682,874,518,544]" pageId="3" pageNumber="109" refId="ref3398" refString="Le Thomas, A. (1969) Annonacees. In: A. Aubreville (Ed.) Flore du Gabon Vol. 16. Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Paris, pp. 1 - 371." type="book" year="1969">Le Thomas 1969</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB7F1FB7152B005FCB15230FBE31345" author="Verdcourt, B." box="[884,1074,518,544]" pageId="3" pageNumber="109" refId="ref4218" refString="Verdcourt, B. (1971 a) Annonaceae. In: Milne-Redhead, E. &amp; Polhill, R. M. (Eds.) Flora of tropical East Africa. East African Community by the Crown Agents for Oversea Governments and Administrations, London." type="book" year="1971">Verdcourt 1971a</bibRefCitation>
). We are not sure if it is glandular tissue and until this is examined in more detail do not refer to it as such.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
